		<ul class="children">
		<li class="comment even depth-3" id="comment-62200">
				<div id="div-comment-62200" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/856804396230c2109515d1314f92ab4c?s=48&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://codinginmysleep.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>David Perry</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://moneydick.com/2012/09/24/bitcoin-and-morality/comment-page-1/#comment-62200">
			September 26, 2012 at 8:30 am</a>		</div>

		<p>One confirmation means that the transaction has been embedded in the most recent block in the chain. Blocks are found on average every 10 minutes, so one confirmation = 10 minutes. 6 confirmations would be 60 minutes.</p>
<p>One confirmation doesn&#8217;t guarantee that a conflicting block solution doesn&#8217;t exist somewhere on the network or that a 51% attack couldn&#8217;t rewrite history, for that your transaction needs to be buried several layers deep, hence the traditional advice that at 6 confirmations transactions should be considered secure.</p>
<p>There are also ways around this attack such as simply communicating with distant nodes about the receipt of conflicting transactions that would warn you of such an attack.</p>

